        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The correspondent and the date are given by CD’s reference in his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2547.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Charles Lyell, 24 [November 1859]</ref>, to ‘a letter dated 22<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.’.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The sentence to which Lyell refers (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref>, p. 201) reads: <quote> It is admitted that the rattlesnake has a poison-fang for its own defence and for the destruction of its prey; but some authors suppose that at the same time this snake is furnished with a rattle for its own injury, namely, to warn its prey to escape.</quote></note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD’s annotation refers to chapter 10 of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5799.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Natural selection</hi></ref>, on the mental powers and instincts of animals. The topics cited by Lyell were drawn from the corresponding chapter on instinct in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref> (chapter 7).</note>
